The '''1543{{nbnd}}1544 Pachecos ''entrada''''' was the final military campaign in the [[Spanish conquest of Yucatan]], which brought three [[kuchkabal|Postclassic Mayan states]] and several Amerindian settlements in the southeastern quarter of the [[Yucatan peninsula]] under the jurisdiction of [[Bacalar|Salamanca de Bacalar]], a ''villa'' of [[Captaincy General of Yucatan|colonial Yucatan]], in [[New Spain]]. It is commonly deemed one of (if not ''the'') bloodiest and cruelest ''entradas'' in the peninsula's conquest, resulting in the deaths of hundreds or thousands, and the displacement of tens of thousands, of Mayan residents.{{notetag
|The [[Yucatec Maya language|Yucatecan Mayan]] orthography in this article follows that of {{harvnb|Barrera Vásquez|Bastarrachea Manzano|Brito Sansores|Vermont Salas|Dzul Góngora|Dzul Poot|1980|pp=41a–44a
}}. At least two other orthographic systems exist {{harv|Lehmann|2018|loc=sec. 2.1, 3
}}, neither of which is used in this article. (Though Mayan toponyms with established English variants, eg Uaymil, which is properly ''Waymil'' {{harv|Barrera Vásquez|Bastarrachea Manzano|Brito Sansores|Vermont Salas|Dzul Góngora|Dzul Poot|1980|pp=917|loc=pt. 1}}, are left unchanged.)
}}{{notetag
|Alternatively, the following have been proposed as the ''final'' campaign in the conquest of Yucatan–
* the quelling of the 1546{{nbnd}}1547 Mayan revolts ({{harvnb|Graham|2011|p=132}}, {{harvnb|Chamberlain|1948|p=236}}, {{sfn|Quezada|2014|p=36}}),
* the [[Spanish conquest of Petén#Conquest of the central lakes|1697 Fall of Nojpeten]].
}}

== Prelude ==

The settlers of [[History of Cuba#Spanish conquest and early colonization (1492 - 1800)|colonial Cuba]] were the first Spaniards to turn their attention to the conquest of [[Kuchkabal|Mayan states in the Yucatan peninsula]]. They were enticed to conquer these after the [[Francisco Hernández de Córdoba (Yucatán conquistador)#1517 Expedition|1517 Hernández de Córdoba expedition]] brought news of splendid (and presumably gold-rich) pre-Columbian cities. The Cubans were soon engrossed in the [[Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire|conquest of the Aztec Empire]], however, leaving the peninsula's subjugation for later.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|pp=11-16}}

Conquest began in earnest upon [[Francisco de Montejo|Francisco de Montejo's]] naming as ''[[adelantado]]'' on 8 November 1526. Montejo's first [[Spanish conquest of Yucatán#Francisco de Montejo, 1527–28|entrada of 1527{{nbnd}}1528]] focussed on the eastern provinces, including [[Uaymil]] and [[Chetumal Province|Chetumal]]. This campaign did not result in Spanish victory, though, requiring a further [[Spanish conquest of Yucatán#Francisco de Montejo and Alonso d' Ávila, 1531–35|1531{{nbnd}}1533 entrada]], which was similarly unsuccessful.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|pp=19-22, 35-65, 97-124}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=30-39}}{{sfn|González Ochoa|2018|loc=para. 7}}{{sfn|García Bernal|2018|loc=para. 13-19}}

By early 1544, the western, northern, and northeastern Mayan provinces had been defeated, and replaced with the ''[[municipios]]'' or districts of [[Campeche]], [[Mérida, Yucatán|Merida]], and [[Valladolid, Yucatán|Valladolid]]. This left only the southeastern provinces (Uaymil, Chetumal, and Dzuluinicob) up for conquest.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|pp=226}}{{sfn|Quezada|2014|p=35}}

== ''Entrada'' ==

=== Northern prong ===
[[File:Valboa throws some Indians, who had committed the terrible sin of sodomy, to the dogs to be torn apart.png|thumb|upright=1.5|Valboa throws some Indians, who had committed the terrible sin of sodomy, to the dogs to be torn apart (1594 by T. de Bry via Univ. Houston)]]

In April 1543, the second ''adelantado'' of Yucatan commissioned Gaspar Pacheco his lieutenant governor, captain general, and ''justicia mayor'' for the conquest of Chetumal, Uaymil, and Amerindian settlements on the Golfo Dulce. Pacheco recruited 25 to 30 ''vecinos'' of Merida for the campaign, naming his son, Melchor, second-in-command, and his nephew, Alonso, third-in-command.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=232}}{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|p=164}}{{sfn|Chamberlain|1939a|p=240}}{{sfn|Graham|2011|pp=112-113, 132-133}}{{notetag
|{{harvnb|López de Cogolludo|1688|p=164}} dates Pacheco's commissioning prior to 3 January 1543, and sets his recruitment of infantrymen in Veracruz. {{harvnb|Graham|2011|pp=112, 133}} dates Pacheco's commissioning during the spring [March{{snds}}June] of 1543.
}}

The party set out of Merida in late 1543 or early 1544. In (recently-conquered) Cochuah, Pacheco compelled war-stricken residents to supply his men with burden-bearers, servants, and provisions, thereby reducing that province to famine. Upon entering Uaymil, Pacheco 'began one of the bloodiest campaigns, and certainly the cruelest, of the entire conquest [of Yucatan].' Here, the lieutenant governor was stricken ill, forcing his retreat to Merida, and transfer of the ''entrada'''s command to his son, Melchor.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=233}}{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|p=164}}{{notetag
|Melchor's second-in-command was, naturally, Gaspar Pacheco's nephew and former third-in-command, Alonso {{harv|Chamberlain|1948|p=233}}.
}}{{notetag
|{{harvnb|López de Cogolludo|1688|p=164}} dates the Pachecos ''entrada'' start and end in 1544. 
}}{{notetag
|It has been suggested that
* Montejo the Younger and Montejo the Nephew would have put a stop to the entrada's excesses, but had no authority to do so {{harv|Chamberlain|1939b|pp=353-354}},
* the adelantado would have put a stop to the excesses, but was unaware of these at the time, being too far removed from the peninsula while in Honduras-Higueras {{harv|Chamberlain|1939b|pp=353-354}},
* friars would have put a stop to the excesses, but were not recruited or did not join the entrada {{harv|Chamberlain|1948|pp=234-235}}.
It has been further noted that Rodrigo Alvarez, an entrada recruit and former secretary to Montejo the Younger, 'sought to persuade the Indians of Uaymil-Chetumal to accept Spanish dominion peacefully, but without the slightest success [...] his efforts to obtain supplies without the use of force [in Cochuah, likewise had] failed completely' {{harv|Chamberlain|1948|p=233}}.
}}

The ''entrada'' was not well-received at Uaymil nor Chetumal. Residents, determined on guerilla warfare, had destroyed their farmland, blocked the thoroughfares, and deserted their settlements.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=233}} The scarcity of food was a strain on both sides, however, as both Spaniards and Mayans were forced to forage for sustenance, quickly leading to a war of attrition.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|pp=233-234}} Facing famine, the Pachecos 'deliberately resorted to wanton acts of cruelty of a kind of which the Montejos and their other principal captains were seldom, if ever guilty.'{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=234}} These acts included–
* killing 'many' or 'numbers' of men and women with the ''garrote'',{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=234}}{{sfn|Ministerio de Fomento|1877|p=80}}
* drowning them in lakes,{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=234}}
* sicking dogs of war on non-combatants until they were dead and their corpses mutilated,{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=234}}{{sfn|Graham|2011|p=133}}{{sfn|Ministerio de Fomento|1877|p=80}}
* severing the hands, ears, and noses of 'many' residents or combatants,{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=234}}{{sfn|Vazquez Barke|2012|pp=26-27}}{{sfn|Graham|2011|p=133}}{{sfn|Ministerio de Fomento|1877|p=80}}
* severing the breasts of women, tying gourds to their feet, and drowning them in lagoons,{{sfn|Graham|2011|p=133}}{{sfn|Ministerio de Fomento|1877|p=80}}
* tying prisoners to stakes, then (non-fatally) whipping them and (non-fatally) shooting arrows at them, until they died of 'natural' causes.{{sfn|Vazquez Barke|2012|pp=26-27}}

These tactics, or attrition itself, 'finally brought the Maya of Uaymil-Chetumal to their knees and the Spaniards to mastery of the province' in 1544. At this point, Melchor Pacheco founded [[Bacalar|Salamanca de Bacalar]], appointing its ''cabildo'', designating its twenty ''vecinos'', and allotting settlements of the conquered provinces in ''encomienda''.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=234}}{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|pp=164-165}}{{sfn|Vazquez Barke|2012|p=27}}{{notetag
|The villa measured some 47 acres, with one section for the 20 ''vecinos'' and another for some 150 Mayan residents (forcibly resettled in the villa). A plaza and church were built in 1546 {{harv|Vazquez Barke|2012|p=31}}, with the parish (christened ''Nuestra Señora de la Purísima Concepción'') overseen by the villa's first resident priest, a secular friar ({{harvnb|Graham|2011|p=142}}, {{harvnb|Jones|1989|p=85}}).
}}{{notetag
|{{harvnb|López de Cogolludo|1688|p=165}} suggests that (''none'', or only some of) the ''conquistadores'' settled in Salamanca, as some (or all surviving ones) returned to Merida, arriving in late 1545.{{block quote
|text=Fundada aquella poblacion [Salamanca de Bacalar], los Conquistadores, que no quedaron por vezinos, dieron buelta à la Ciudad de Merida, y noticia à su General de lo sucedido, con que se començò à gozar de mas quietud, y esto dize el Bachiller Valencia, fue por fines del año de mil y quinientos y quarenta y cinco.
|author={{harvnb|López de Cogolludo|1688|p=165}}
}}
}}

=== Southern prong ===

In 1544, the Pachecos pushed southwards through Dzuluinicob and Manche Ch'ol and Mopan territory towards the Golfo Dulce.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|p=234}}{{sfn|González Cicero|1976|pp=21, 83}}{{notetag
|It is unclear whether this was before or after the founding of Salamanca (cf previous citation).
}}{{notetag
|It is unclear whether Dzuluinicob was conquered during the southern prong of the Pachecos entrada towards the Golfo Dulce. Tipu, capital of Dzuluinicob, 'does not appear on a tribute list for 1544, but is recorded as an already established encomienda town in 1568, which indicates that it had functioned as part of an encomienda for some time [;] [t]his, plus what is now [2011] known about the extent of the Pacheco conquest, suggests strongly that Tipu was brought into the encomienda system not long after the [1543{{nbnd}}1544] Pacheco conquest' ({{harvnb|Graham|2011|p=361|loc=item no. 60}}, {{harvnb|Jones|1989|pp=17, 44, 51}}).
}}

== Aftermath ==
=== Population collapse ===

It is generally agreed that the Pachecos' victory soon proved pyrrhic. Uaymil and Chetumal, in particular, were said to be heavily populated, wealthy provinces prior to conquest. The district Salamanca de Bacalar inherited, however, was sparsely settled and poor, and remained so throughout.{{sfn|Chamberlain|1948|pp=235-236}}{{sfn|Vazquez Barke|2012|pp=27-28}}{{sfn|Chamberlain|1939b|p=353}}{{sfn|Landa|2011|p=9}}{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|pp=164-165}}{{sfn|Ministerio de Fomento|1877|p=80}}{{sfn|Morandi|2010|p=39}}{{notetag
|It has been suggested that 'large numbers' of residents resettled in the [[Peten Itza Kingdom]] 'in an attempt to place themselves beyond Spanish reach forever' ({{harvnb|Chamberlain|1948|p=236}}, {{harvnb|Chamberlain|1939b|p=353}}, {{harv|Graham|2011|p=133}}).
}}{{notetag
|During 1544{{nbnd}}1639, the villa's population averaged 75 (including both Spanish vecinos and Mayan naborías or servants) ({{harvnb|Morandi|2010|p=39}}, {{harvnb|Jones|1989|pp=71-74}}).
}}

